You can see the size
of the watermark,

00:48:57.650 --> 00:49:02.330
and that is the exact same
paper used in the production

00:49:02.330 --> 00:49:07.230
of that Dante book that
was printed in Florence.

00:49:07.230 --> 00:49:14.230
So that was an exciting match.

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:20.370
Atlases are also a great source of
Fabriano paper and that's partly

00:49:20.370 --> 00:49:24.560
because they required large
sheets and sheets of good quality

00:49:24.560 --> 00:49:29.650
and so this [inaudible]
watermark is a very popular one

00:49:29.650 --> 00:49:32.280
for the oversized sheets that
were produced in Fabriano

00:49:32.280 --> 00:49:35.890
and we have I think the largest
collection of [inaudible] atlases

00:49:35.890 --> 00:49:40.820
in maybe the U.S., many of
which were printed in Italy

00:49:40.820 --> 00:49:43.870
and some printed in Rome.

00:49:43.870 --> 00:49:49.020
And I think that using the
watermarks to date the making

00:49:49.020 --> 00:49:51.040
of the maps would be very useful

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:55.430 position:56%
because sometimes the same paper
was used for many different editions

00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:59.590
of these volumes, and it
certainly would be a good project.

00:49:59.590 --> 00:50:04.830
I found them often to
have Fabriano paper.

00:50:06.110 --> 00:50:11.050
This is a manuscript from
the manuscript division.

00:50:11.050 --> 00:50:16.420
It's called the Amoretti Codex
after the owner of the codex

00:50:16.420 --> 00:50:22.090
who is a Roman priest, but it's
actually a copy of a letter written

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:30.730
by Amerigo Vespucci after his
voyages in the new world and it's

00:50:30.730 --> 00:50:36.440 position:56%
on a paper that has the same hunting
horn watermark that we saw earlier.

00:50:36.440 --> 00:50:41.990
And this is a very important piece
because the original has been lost

00:50:41.990 --> 00:50:45.940
and so we have a copy of this
that is a contemporary copy

00:50:45.940 --> 00:50:49.490
and once again, the watermark
can help date the time,

00:50:49.490 --> 00:50:54.140
at least it can tell you that
the item was not done before a

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:55.660
certain time.

00:50:55.660 --> 00:51:00.650
It can't necessarily tell you
how late it is, but anyway.

00:51:00.650 --> 00:51:03.240
Of course, some of the
earliest printed books

00:51:03.240 --> 00:51:07.220
in italy were religious text
and this Bible that was printed

00:51:07.220 --> 00:51:10.510
in Naples was also
on oversized paper.

00:51:10.510 --> 00:51:12.990
And it's about 450 pages.

00:51:12.990 --> 00:51:17.180
It's a [inaudible]
Bible,and many of the papers

00:51:17.180 --> 00:51:21.260
in it are Fabriano including
this well known watermark.

00:51:21.260 --> 00:51:26.350
It's maybe a little bit hard to
see here but here is the same paper

00:51:26.350 --> 00:51:31.040
that was present in
the Fabriano archives.

00:51:31.040 --> 00:51:38.070
That same shear patter, which
since there was a very active wool

00:51:38.070 --> 00:51:41.920
industry and there was probably
a lot of shearing of sheep,

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:45.590
it was a symbol that comes
from the local industry.

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:51.200
It was interesting to me that
this particular book was printed

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:54.750
in four different cities
at the same time in Naples,

00:51:54.750 --> 00:51:57.220
Florence, Rome and Venice.

00:51:57.220 --> 00:52:02.890
This book that is by [inaudible]
on great men of ancient Rome

00:52:02.890 --> 00:52:06.940 position:56%
and all four versions of the book --
they weren't printed the same year,

00:52:06.940 --> 00:52:10.160
but they were printed within
15 years of each other,

00:52:10.160 --> 00:52:12.470 position:56%
and they were all on Fabriano paper.

00:52:12.470 --> 00:52:16.080
Different watermarks but
all from the same source.

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:21.590
An important printer to
mention who is often associated

00:52:21.590 --> 00:52:27.280
with Fabriano papers is the printer
Gershom Sancino who immigrated

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:33.730 position:56%
to Italy from Germany and settled in
the [inaudible] region for a while

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:35.900
and did quite a bit
of printing there both

00:52:35.900 --> 00:52:40.960
in Hebrew [inaudible]
type and in Roman type.

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:42.570
He's very celebrated there.

00:52:42.570 --> 00:52:46.470
There's a street named after him
and in the archive, there's a list

00:52:46.470 --> 00:52:51.580
of the receipts for the paper that
he purchased for Fabriano for many

00:52:51.580 --> 00:52:56.480
of these volumes, and he's still
well known for the way that he laid

00:52:56.480 --> 00:53:00.410 position:56%
out the page in this beautiful
pattern and here's the original text

00:53:00.410 --> 00:53:03.250
and the commentary around
it, and I understand

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:08.460
that even contemporary
[inaudible] that are used

00:53:08.460 --> 00:53:11.740 position:56%
in services have still retained some

00:53:11.740 --> 00:53:15.520
of his same original
typography pattern.

00:53:15.520 --> 00:53:19.330
He was not always able to
use the finest quality paper

00:53:19.330 --> 00:53:25.070
for his Hebrew text, but he did
as I say also print on commission.

00:53:25.070 --> 00:53:28.070
He printed the statutes
of the city of [inaudible]

00:53:28.070 --> 00:53:32.880
and he also printed this
cardinal's book and in this case,

00:53:32.880 --> 00:53:36.330
he was able to use
the expensive paper.

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:44.820
Many other objects in the
library were found that were made

00:53:44.820 --> 00:53:48.150
on Fabriano paper including
a lot of fine prints here,

00:53:48.150 --> 00:53:51.940
this [inaudible] print by Ugo
de Carpi along with a number

00:53:51.940 --> 00:53:55.320
of other prints from the
Pembrook album [inaudible]

00:53:55.320 --> 00:54:00.470
and this is another important
symbol associated with Fabriano.

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:05.720
It's a ladder and there was the
Scala family who was very involved

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:08.300
in papermaking and [speaking
foreign language] means ladder

00:54:08.300 --> 00:54:09.600
and also [speaking
foreign language].

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:14.900
In this case, we had [speaking
foreign language] and Scala family.

00:54:14.900 --> 00:54:20.460
They probably owned the mill
that used this watermark.

00:54:20.460 --> 00:54:27.240
And another very lovely
print by Domenico Beccafumi,

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:29.220
another chiaroscuro woodcut.

00:54:29.220 --> 00:54:34.090
He was an artist from Siena and
although Siena also made paper,

00:54:34.090 --> 00:54:37.770
their industry was begun
by Fabriano craftsmen

00:54:37.770 --> 00:54:45.370
and they still imported the
oversized fine quality paper

00:54:45.370 --> 00:54:46.670
from Fabriano.

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:50.400
I think artists also liked it
because it was quite substantial.

00:54:50.400 --> 00:54:53.430
And if you have to put
your print as in this case

00:54:53.430 --> 00:54:57.570
through the press several times,
in this case at least twice,

00:54:57.570 --> 00:55:02.580
you have to have a paper that's
strong enough to withstand that.

00:55:04.050 --> 00:55:10.910
Now for paper conservators who are
here, this is an important slide

00:55:10.910 --> 00:55:14.670
for telling you how you can
identify Fabriano paper even

00:55:14.670 --> 00:55:17.330
if you are not sure
about the watermark.

00:55:17.330 --> 00:55:21.560
Their mold style was
such that the watermark

00:55:21.560 --> 00:55:31.280
after about 1350 was always
in between two chain lines

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.270
with a chain line in the middle

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:35.960
that was called the
supplemental chain line

00:55:35.960 --> 00:55:37.260
or the [speaking foreign language].

00:55:37.260 --> 00:55:40.560
But you can't really
see very well here,

00:55:40.560 --> 00:55:44.300
but it didn't have a
wooden support behind it.

00:55:44.300 --> 00:55:47.490
In the case of this paper,
this paper was made with a mold

00:55:47.490 --> 00:55:50.530
that had wooden supports
behind each chain line.

00:55:50.530 --> 00:55:54.450
But you see where the watermark is,
it was actually a chain line there,

00:55:54.450 --> 00:55:56.930
but there's no wooden
support behind it.

00:55:56.930 --> 00:56:00.090
And that's a clue that the
paper was made certainly

00:56:00.090 --> 00:56:02.360
in the mold style of Fabriano.

00:56:02.360 --> 00:56:06.760
You have to find an exact match
of the watermark itself also

00:56:06.760 --> 00:56:08.790
because papers were copied.

00:56:08.790 --> 00:56:13.310
But this is an important
feature to know.

00:56:13.310 --> 00:56:18.680
The Zonghi collection that's in
the museum has been published,

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:23.020
but it was a contraband publication
where the tracings were stolen

00:56:23.020 --> 00:56:26.530
out of Italy by the person
who had done them and sold

00:56:26.530 --> 00:56:30.890
to a Dutch paper historian,
and they were published

00:56:30.890 --> 00:56:33.380
by the Hilversom Society
in the 1950's,

00:56:33.380 --> 00:56:35.910
but it's still a very,
very useful book.

00:56:35.910 --> 00:56:39.220
The unfortunate thing about this
book is that unlike [inaudible]

00:56:39.220 --> 00:56:41.610
for those of you who
are paper historians,

00:56:41.610 --> 00:56:45.740
it doesn't give you the exact
manuscript that each one

00:56:45.740 --> 00:56:48.950
of these watermarks
is associated with.

00:56:48.950 --> 00:56:52.160
So you just have to trust that
the date that they're giving you

00:56:52.160 --> 00:56:54.050
in the book is the real one.

00:56:54.050 --> 00:57:02.660
But with the new acquisition of
the larger collection by the mill,

00:57:02.660 --> 00:57:06.130
the registry book that is
associated with every single one

00:57:06.130 --> 00:57:09.970
of these papers was also
part of the collection.

00:57:09.970 --> 00:57:13.150
So now there's going to be a lot
more information for historians

00:57:13.150 --> 00:57:17.670 position:56%
to date papers by these
watermarks, and the digital versions

00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:20.930
of them will give you more
information about the paper itself.

00:57:20.930 --> 00:57:25.890
So while this book is still useful,
just pay attention to what's coming

00:57:25.890 --> 00:57:29.010
in the future because
it will be an addition.

00:57:30.470 --> 00:57:34.030
So here's a watermark from
that second collection,

00:57:34.030 --> 00:57:37.240
and some people have asked me okay,
well so you spent all this time

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:42.800
on medieval and renaissance
paper, what is your next chapter?

00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:44.910
Are you going to stick
with Fabriano?

00:57:44.910 --> 00:57:49.910
And one thing that really interests
me is 20th century papers made

00:57:49.910 --> 00:57:56.920
in Fabriano and their use by
artists in America as well all

00:57:56.920 --> 00:58:01.110
over the world, and this is a
wonderful drawing by Georg O'Keefe

00:58:01.110 --> 00:58:06.540
in the Milwaukee Art Museum
that has a [inaudible] watermark

00:58:06.540 --> 00:58:09.090
that you can see even
through the frame.

00:58:09.090 --> 00:58:14.710
So I'd like to explore the use
of more modern Fabriano papers

00:58:14.710 --> 00:58:16.850
by artists working today.

00:58:16.850 --> 00:58:18.650
So, thank you very much.

00:58:18.650 --> 00:58:26.650
[ Applause ]

